Driving on the Moon? Hot dog! üå≠‚Å£  This vehicle ‚Äì which looks like the front half of a famous sausage-shaped car ‚Äì is one of many lunar rover concepts created for the Apollo program. Part of preparation for the missions was figuring out a design for a lunar vehicle that would allow astronauts a greater range of mobility.‚Å£  Designers had a lot to consider when creating a Moon rover: weak gravity, a lack of atmosphere, and extreme temperature, to name a few. These factors, frank-ly, imposed severe requirements on the vehicle. Each concept provided data that helped in designing the Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV) that made its debut during the Apollo 15 mission (swipe to see it).‚Å£  The LRV, which did not end up being glizzy-shaped, drove at a blistering 5 miles per hour (8 km per hour). Astronaut Dave Scott said of the first trip on the Moon, ‚ÄúThis is a super way to travel ‚Ä¶ This is great ‚Ä¶ and it‚Äôs easy to drive ‚Ä¶ No problem at all.‚Äù Sounds like a bun-believable experience.‚Å£  During their 67-hour stay on the Moon, Scott and fellow astronaut Jim Irwin used the LRV to make three separate motor trips to explore the rim of Hadley Rille, deep crater edges, and the Apennine Mountains. The LRV more than met its goal of increasing movement, as Scott and Irwin covered almost four times as much lunar terrain as the total covered by the crews of the Apollo 11, 12, and 14 missions before them.‚Å£  Image descriptions:‚Å£ 1. An astronaut stands near a lunar rover concept that looks like the front half of the Weinermobile attached by a hose to a platform with large fan-like wheels. The front half has the same wheels, as well as an open hatch on the side and small windows in the front. The photo is in black and white.‚Å£  2. At right, astronaut Jim Irwin works at the LRV on the Moon. The rover looks noticeably different from the concept vehicle in the previous image. It has four tires that look more like ones you‚Äôd see on a car, except they are made of wire. The high gain antenna stands out on the rover‚Äôs right side. St. George crater appears in the distance behind Irwin‚Äôs head.‚Å£‚Å£  Credit: NASA  #NASA #Apollo #VehicleDesign #HotDog #NowWereHungry

Not your ordinary spiral...  At first glance, UGC 11397 looks like a typical spiral galaxy: two graceful arms, illuminated by stars, stretch out from its core. The heart of UGC 11397 hides what makes this galaxy unique, though‚Äîa supermassive black hole 174 million times the mass of our Sun. And it's still growing.  Material trapped by the black hole emits light in frequencies from radio waves to gamma rays, but thick clouds of dust hide most of this from view in the visible spectrum. X-ray emissions, though, helped astronomers uncover this cosmic phenomenon.  This image of UGC 11397 was taken by our orbiting @NASAHubble telescope.  Image description: A spiral galaxy burns bright, with twin spiral arms snaking out in shades of white, blue, and dark red. The background surrounding it has a handful of shining stars.  Credit: ESA/Hubble & NASA, M. J. Koss, A. J. Barth  #NASA #Space #Universe #Galaxy #BlackHole

That's no moon. Oh wait. Yes it is.  This is a photo of Mars, taken before dawn by our Perseverance rover, and that tiny dot in the sky is Deimos, the smaller of Mars' two moons. Deimos is much, *much* smaller than Earth's Moon: it's about 9 by 7 by 6.8 miles (15x12x11 km) in size. Because it's so tiny, its gravitational forces make it more of a lump than a sphere.  Because it was taken at night with a long exposure time, this image of the Martian night sky is a little more grainy than other photos we've received from our Perseverance and Curiosity rovers. Would the night sky on Mars be filled with twinkling stars like we‚Äôre used to seeing on Earth? Get the full story from @NASAJPL in an Instagram Reel they published on April 15, 2025. All eyes on me ‚òÑÔ∏è‚Å£  ‚Å£ When @NASAHubble captured this image of Comet ISON on April 30, 2013, the comet was closer to the Sun than Jupiter's orbit. First spotted 585 million miles away in September 2012, the comet became the subject of a massive global observation campaign incorporating space-based and ground-based telescopes and participation from citizen scientists and professional and amateur astronomers. Why was ISON so special?‚Å£  ‚Å£ As a comet travels through the solar system, it faces many perils. Before it reaches Mars, the Sun‚Äôs radiation begins to boil its water. A giant ejection of solar material from the Sun could rip its tail off. And, if it survives all this, the intense radiation and pressure as it flies near the surface of the sun could destroy it altogether. Comet ISON was making its first trip around the Sun, which meant it was still made of pristine matter from the earliest days of the solar system‚Äôs formation. ISON was, like all comets, a dirty snowball made up of dust and frozen gases like water, ammonia, methane, and carbon dioxide ‚Äì some of the fundamental building blocks that scientists believe led to the formation of the planets 4.5 billion years ago.‚Å£  ‚Å£ By tracking its journey, scientists could learn what the comet was made of and how it reacted to its environment. They could also learn more about the origins of the solar system.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Just prior to its closest approach to the Sun on Nov. 28, 2013, Comet ISON went through a major heating event, and was torn to pieces. What remained of Comet ISON appeared to brighten and spread out, then fade. The legacy of the data collected during this great observation, however, would go on for years as scientists analyzed what they found.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Image description: A white comet with a long, fuzzy tail rises up diagonally to the right. All around it are stars and galaxies, which dot the blackness of space.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Credit: NASA‚Å£  ‚Å£ #NASA #Comet #Space #Hubble #Telescope #SolarSystem

Star power üåü   The Carina Nebula complex is one of the most energetic star-forming areas in our galaxy ‚Äî within it lies the Keyhole Nebula, pictured here by the European Southern Observatory. Our Stratospheric Observatory for Infrared Astronomy (SOFIA) was able to detect the magnetic field streamlines shown over this image.   Eta Carinae, a huge active star neighboring the Keyhole Nebula, could have influenced the nebula's shape with its strong winds. Data from SOFIA's observations show that the magnetic fields in the loop seem affected by the star's strong wing. The magnetic field spreads out in a fan shape, matching the wind from Eta Carinae. This shows that the magnetic field is being disturbed by the star's energy.   The magnetic field in the loop is much weaker than the star's wind, which means that while magnetic fields are important in the early stages of star formation, they don‚Äôt do much to stop the cloud from being broken apart by the energy from massive stars. Scientists now wonder if the same is true in other places where big stars are forming.   Image description: The Keyhole Nebula glows in shades of blue, pink and purple. In the center of the nebula, the magnetic fields are identified by what resembles a wind pattern, moving in swirls around a loop in the center. Stars dot the background of the image in shades of pink and blue.   Credit: NASA, the SOFIA science team, Y. Seo; ESO   #NASA #Space #Stars #Astronomy #Keyhole #Nebula #MagneticFields

Saturn‚Äôs greatest hits, now on vinyl üé∂‚Å£ ‚Å£ Saturn and its innermost rings look like a close-up of a record in this image taken by Cassini, a sophisticated robotic spacecraft sent to study Saturn and its complex system of rings and moons in unprecedented detail. For more than a decade, Cassini shared the wonders of Saturn, its spectacular rings, and its family of icy moons.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Saturn's rings are thought to be pieces of comets, asteroids, or shattered moons that broke up before they reached the planet, torn apart by Saturn's powerful gravity. They are made of billions of small chunks of ice and rock coated with other materials such as dust. The ring particles mostly range from tiny, dust-sized icy grains to chunks as big as a house. A few particles are as large as mountains.‚Å£ ‚Å£ P.S. This picture doesn‚Äôt make any noise, but we have transformed other photos into sound with data sonification. You can listen to some here ‚Äì and even learn how to make your own! https://go.nasa.gov/SpaceSounds‚Å£ ‚Å£ Image description: A close-up black-and-white photo of Saturn‚Äôs rings. The rings look like grooves on a record. On the right, the rings cast a dark shadow on Saturn, which appears white here.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/Space Science Institute‚Å£ ‚Å£ #NASA #Saturn #Rings #Planet #Space

More passion, more energy üï∫   The amazing dancing lights we can see close to the North and South Poles of Earth happen on other planets, too, and @NASAWebb captured new details of auroras on the biggest planet in our solar system. Observations show that auroras on Jupiter are huge in size and are also hundreds of times more energetic than auroras on Earth.   On Earth, auroras are caused by solar storms. When charged particles rain down on the upper atmosphere, it excites gases and causes them to glow colors of red, green, and purple. On Jupiter, there's an additional source of auroras ‚Äî the magnetic field of the gas giant grabs charged particles from its surroundings, including its tumultuous volcanic moon, Io.  Io‚Äôs estimated 400 volcanoes spew particles that escape the moon‚Äôs gravity and orbit Jupiter. During a solar storm, a barrage of charged particles is unleashed onto the planet. Jupiter‚Äôs large and powerful magnetic field captures charged particles and accelerates them to tremendous speeds. These speedy particles slam into the planet‚Äôs atmosphere at high energies, which excites the gas and causes it to glow.   Now, Webb‚Äôs unique capabilities are providing new insights into the auroras on Jupiter. The telescope‚Äôs sensitivity allows astronomers to increase the shutter speed to capture the quick changes of auroral features.   Visual descriptions:  1. The planet Jupiter as seen in near-infrared light. Its clouds are dark blue and white in color, with some red spots within the clouds, while its poles are tinged with green, yellow, and red. A box over the North Pole is overlaid with more data in shades of orange, displaying auroras as arcs and rings.   2. The inset area is shown in larger detail. This video is a close-up near-infrared look at Jupiter‚Äôs North Pole, in shades of orange. Swirling auroras cover the pole.   Credit: ESA/Webb, NASA, CSA, J. Nichols (University of Leicester), M. Zamani (ESA/Webb)   #NASA #Space #JWST #NASAWebb #Telescope #Jupiter #SolarSystem #Aurora

Hotter than the bluest flame üî•‚Äâ ‚Äâ Our friends at the @EuropeanSpaceAgency recently shared a dazzling young star cluster as astronomers have never seen it before.‚Äâ  ‚Äâ This star cluster, NGC 346, is located in the Small Magellanic Cloud, a satellite galaxy of the Milky Way about 200,000 light-years away. Though @NASAHubble has studied this cluster before, this image is the first to combine Hubble‚Äôs observations made at infrared, optical, and ultraviolet wavelengths, giving an intricate view into the star-forming factory. ‚Äâ ‚Äâ NGC 346 is home to more than 2,500 newborn stars. The cluster‚Äôs most massive stars, which are many times more massive than our Sun, blaze with intense blue light in this image. Researchers used two sets of observations taken 11 years apart to trace the motions of NGC 346‚Äôs stars, revealing them to be spiraling in toward the center of the cluster. Time to power up üîã‚Äâ  ‚Äâ The International Space Station (@ISS) gets its power from the largest power source in our solar system - the Sun. Most spacecraft use solar panels to harness the Sun's continuous energy and provide power to keep the spacecraft working and at the right temperature.‚Äâ  ‚Äâ Solar panels (like this set of solar arrays on the station) must be designed around two key factors: size and reliability. The size of the panels affects the cost of launch, while the reliability determines how the panels withstand the harsh environment of space, including temperature swings, radiation, and micrometeoroid impacts.‚Äâ  ‚Äâ The current wingspan of our space station's solar array, 356 feet (109 meters), is longer than the world's largest passenger aircraft. The solar panel pictured above is one of eight that generate approximately 95 kilowatts of power for a total of up to 215 kilowatts (215,000 watts) of power available to keep the station running. For comparison, an active computer and monitor may use up to 270 watts, and a small refrigerator uses about 725 watts.‚Äâ  ‚Äâ Image description: Moonlight casts a blue light on a set of the International Space Station's main solar arrays and rollout solar arrays, as they are crowned by Earth's atmospheric glow, at an orbit of 259 miles (417 km) above the North Pacific Ocean.‚Äâ  ‚Äâ Credit: NASA‚Äâ  ‚Äâ #NASA #Space #ISS #SpaceStation #Orbit #Earth #Astronauts #Energy #Power

Tag someone you lava üåã  Io, the third-largest moon of Jupiter, is the most volcanically active world in the solar system. Extreme tidal forces from the gas giant (and nearby moons Ganymede and Europa) generate tremendous heat within Io, triggering eruptions from the moon's subsurface crust.  Though Io has hundreds of huge volcanoes, it was still an impressive sight for NASA's Galileo spacecraft to spot an eruption in action when it flew past the moon in 1997. Launched in 1989, Galileo was the first spacecraft to enter Jupiter's orbit, studying the planet and its moons for nearly 10 years.  Image description: Half of Io, a shiny, chrome-colored world with a maze of rough patches, is seen from space at a close distance. Near the very top, a small blue burst indicates a volcanic eruption.  Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech, DLR  #NASA #Space #Moon #Io #Jupiter #Volcano #Eruption

This image is a combination of X-ray data from NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory and optical data by amateur astronomer John Stone ‚Äî but the @NASAChandraXray team has also just released a new 3D visualization of the Cygnus Loop. It visualizes how the blast wave from the explosion interacts with an isolated cloud of the interstellar medium (that is, dust and gas in between the stars). You can view that 3D model and others like it at nasa.gov/chandra.  Image description: In the composite image, the remnant resembles a wispy cloud in oranges, blues, purples, and whites, shaped like a backwards letter C. Don't let anyone treat you like a yellow starburst. You're a pink starburst. üíñ  What you're seeing here is a starburst in a distant galaxy. The Cigar Galaxy, located 12 million light-years from Earth, gets its name from its thin, cigar-like appearance. The Cigar Galaxy is actually a spiral galaxy, like our own Milky Way‚Äîwe're just seeing it on its side.   Gravitational forces from its galactic neighbor (known as M81, or Messier 81) are resonating through the Cigar Galaxy, causing stars to form at an extraordinarily high rate. Eventually, though, the Cigar Galaxy will burn itself out: when it runs out of new material to make stars, likely in tens of millions of years, the starburst will subside.  This image of the Cigar Galaxy was unveiled by our @NASAHubble telescope team in 2006. The red in the image represents hydrogen and infrared light, indicating starburst activity. The blue and greenish-yellow colors are visible wavelengths of light.   Image description: A ghostly, bluish-yellow oval is intersected by a wispy hourglass-shaped cloud of red. Mountain (STScI), and P. Puxley (NSF)  #NASA #Space #Universe #Galaxy #Hubble #Astrophotography #Starburst

‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know why I go to extremes.‚Äù ‚ÄîJupiter (probably)‚Äâ  ‚Äâ The planet is home to fierce jet streams, polar cyclones bigger than Australia, the most powerful aurora and harshest radiation belts in the solar system - and we‚Äôre just scratching the surface. ‚Äâ  ‚Äâ Data from Juno helped develop a new model to better understand the fast-moving jet stream that encircles Jupiter‚Äôs cyclone-festooned north pole. Juno took the first-ever temperature measurement of the cap of Jupiter‚Äôs atmosphere above the north pole: it‚Äôs about 52¬∫F (11¬∫C) cooler than its surroundings and is encircled by winds exceeding 100 mph (161 kph). Unlike hurricanes on Earth, which typically occur in isolation and at lower latitudes, Jupiter‚Äôs massive northern polar cyclone and the eight cyclones that encircle it are confined to the polar region. Jupiter‚Äôs cyclones cluster together while approaching the pole, and their motion slows as they begin interacting with neighboring cyclones.‚Äâ  ‚Äâ Image description: An enhanced-color image split into two frames shows Jupiter‚Äôs northern high latitudes from an altitude of about 36,000 miles (58,000 km) above the giant planet‚Äôs cloud tops during the spacecrafts 69th flyby on Jan. 28, 2025. Add a pop of color! üé®‚Å£  ‚Å£ When the cameras on NASA‚Äôs New Horizons spacecraft first spotted the large reddish polar region on Pluto‚Äôs largest moon, Charon, mission scientists knew two things: they‚Äôd never seen anything like it elsewhere in our solar system, and they couldn‚Äôt wait to get the story behind it.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Turns out Pluto is something of a graffiti artist ‚Äì methane gas escapes from Pluto‚Äôs atmosphere, becomes ‚Äútrapped‚Äù by Charon‚Äôs gravity, and freezes to the cold, icy surface at the moon‚Äôs pole. When it‚Äôs springtime on Charon, the returning sunlight triggers the frozen methane to change back into gas, which leaves behind heavier chemical compounds. Sunlight further irradiates those leftovers into reddish material that has slowly accumulated on Charon‚Äôs poles over millions of years.‚Å£  ‚Å£ The image combines blue, red, and infrared images taken by New Horizons‚Äô Ralph/Multispectral Visual Imaging Camera (MVIC); the colors are processed to best highlight the variation of surface properties across Charon. New Horizons was the first spacecraft to explore Pluto up close. In early 2019, New Horizons flew past its second major science target ‚Äì Arrokoth, the most distant object ever explored up close.‚Å£  Image description: Pluto‚Äôs largest moon, Charon, is gray with a jagged line of fractures and canyons going across it diagonally. There are many craters visible, especially on the bottom and right sides. At the top, in a region informally named Mordor Macula, Charon is a deep, rusty red.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Credit: NASA/JHUAPL/SwRI‚Å£  ‚Å£ #NASA #Pluto #Moon #Astronomy #Science

Can we get an encore?  A planetary nebula located just 4,600 light-years away in the Milky Way galaxy puts on a spectacular display at the end of a giant star's life. The image itself was the final work of one of @NASAHubble's instruments: the Wide Field and Planetary Camera 2 (WFPC2). First installed in 1993, the WFPC2 was replaced in 2009 by the Wide Field Camera 3 during Hubble‚Äôs final servicing mission.  The swirling, paint-like clouds in the darkness of space are clouds of ionized atoms thrown into space by a dying star. Its red giant star had exhausted its available fuel and shed its last layers of gas, enabling nuclear fusion as its compact core begins to contract further. The exposed core reaches extremely hot temperatures, radiating ultraviolet light that energizes the enormous clouds of gas cast off by the star.   In this image, red and orange indicate nitrogen, green is hydrogen, and blue shows oxygen. The spectacle is bittersweet, as the brief phase of fusion in the core will end after only tens of thousands of years, leaving a white dwarf that will never illuminate the clouds around it again.  Image description: A glowing, jagged ring encircles a small central region of greenish clouds, making it appear like a hole torn in fabric. This ‚Äúhole‚Äù is itself encircled by a band of silvery-blue clouds and a larger, fainter, yellow ring of gas. Puffy, smoky clouds of orange and red gas billow out from there into a large oval nebula, fading into the dark background of space dotted by stars.  Credit: @EuropeanSpaceAgency/Hubble & NASA, K. Noll  #NASA #Space #Hubble #MilkyWay #Stars #Nebula #Encore #Telescope

Livin' life in low Earth orbit   For nearly 25 years, @NASAAstronauts have been living and working aboard the International Space Station. Some have only stayed for a few days, while some have lived in space for over a year at a time. (Astronaut Frank Rubio holds the NASA record, with a 371-day stay.) Some have traveled to the @ISS several times, while some are making their first visit‚Äîlike NASA's Nichole Ayers, seen here opening the hatch to the station's Kibo laboratory. Ayers launched to the station on NASA's SpaceX Crew-10 mission, which lifted off from @NASAKennedy on March 14.  The International Space Station is an orbiting laboratory, built to help us learn how to live in space while making life better back on Earth. We work with crew members and researchers from around the world to study human health, medicine and biology, materials research, Earth science and countless other scientific disciplines. (Visit nasa.gov/iss-research for more info.) Now, we're working with commercial partners on a new generation of space stations, making space more accessible and affordable as we send humans to the Moon and Mars.  Image description: Astronaut Nichole Ayers floats above a large, circular hatch in the International Space Station. She is looking down at the hatch and wearing a crimson long-sleeved shirt; her blond hair floats above her head. The hatch is hinged open to reveal the circular doorway into the station's Kibo laboratory; behind her, the walls of the station are mostly white panels, with a few cords and pieces of hardware.  Credit: NASA  #NASA #Space #Aerospace #Universe #Astronaut #SpaceStation #ISS

Heading into the weekend like... üßë‚ÄçüöÄ  On February 7, 1984, astronaut Bruce McCandless II became the first human in history to go on a spacewalk without a connection to their spacecraft. McCandless soared outside the space shuttle Challenger with the Manned Maneuvering Unit (MMU), a propulsion device on the back of his spacesuit that used two tanks of hydrogen and 24 nozzles to move him around.   In this iconic photo, taken by Challenger pilot Hoot Gibson, McCandless was just a few meters away from the shuttle, but further MMU flights by McCandless and astronaut Robert L. Stewart took them more than 300 feet (91 meters) into space. The MMU was used for several more flights in the 1980s. Today's @NASAAstronauts now wear SAFER (Simplified Aid For EVA Rescue), a smaller, simpler thruster system, in case they accidentally become untethered on a spacewalk.  Image description: An astronaut, wearing a full spacesuit and a large backpack, floats above Earth. Earth's blue seas and thin white clouds arc over the bottom half of this image; the astronaut is just above Earth's curvature. From the perspective of the photograph, he is leaning approximately 45 degrees to the right.  Credit: NASA/Hoot Gibson  #NASA #Space #Earth #Universe #Spacewalk #Astronaut #TGIF

View from a lifeboat  Apollo 13 astronauts Jim Lovell, Fred Haise, and Jack Swigert launched from @NASAKennedy on April 11, 1970. They were headed to the Fra Mauro region of the Moon for the third lunar landing ever. Everything seemed to be going smoothly until the third day of the mission, when an oxygen tank ruptured and Swigert uttered those famous words: ‚ÄúHouston, we‚Äôve had a problem here.‚Äù  The new mission plan was to abandon the Moon landing, loop around the Moon, and get the crew home safely as quickly as possible. The crew needed to go into ‚Äúlifeboat mode,‚Äù using the lunar module Aquarius to save the spacecraft and crew. The Apollo 13 crew took this photo of the Moon from the lunar module as they passed by.  On April 17, the crew returned to Earth, splashing down in the Pacific Ocean near Samoa. The Apollo 13 mission is sometimes called a ‚Äúsuccessful failure‚Äù: Though the crew couldn‚Äôt achieve their scientific goals, the rescue mission was a huge victory for NASA. The lessons learned from Apollo 13 were rapidly applied to the remaining Apollo missions and continue to guide us at NASA today.  Image description: The Moon‚Äôs gray, cratered surface is visible from the Apollo 13 lunar module. To the right, the shut-down command module covers some of the view. There are marks that look like plus signs overlaid on the photo.  Credit: NASA  #NASA #History #SpaceHistory #Apollo13 #Moon #FailureIsNotAnOption

For 20 years, @NASAHubble has been studying Uranus... and learning more about its gas.  Uranus' atmosphere is mostly hydrogen and helium, with a small amount of methane‚Äîbut that methane gives Uranus its distinctive cyan color. Our orbiting Hubble telescope studied Uranus between 2002 and 2022 and found that unlike other gas giants, Uranus has much less methane near its poles.   Hubble also tracked complex circulation patterns in the planet's atmosphere, giving scientists a deeper look into Uranus.  This classic image of Uranus was taken not by Hubble, but by NASA's Voyager 2 spacecraft as it flew by the planet on Jan. 14, 1986. It‚Äôs time to cast your spell on the night‚Å£  ‚Å£ About 5,550 light-years away in our galaxy, there‚Äôs a magical light show going on. This region is a cluster of clusters, containing at least three clusters of young stars, including many hot, massive, luminous stars. These hot, young stars emit radiation, which energizes the cooler gas in the cloud that surrounds them.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Astronomers call this object and others like it ‚ÄúHII‚Äù (pronounced ‚ÄúH-two‚Äù) regions. An HII region is created when the radiation from hot, young stars strips away the electrons from neutral hydrogen atoms in the surrounding gas to form clouds of ionized hydrogen, which is denoted scientifically as ‚ÄúHII.‚Äù Scientists study these areas with telescopes like @NASAChandraXray because young stars are bright in X-rays. Also, X-rays can penetrate the shrouds of gas and dust surrounding these infant stars, allowing astronomers to see how stars are formed with details that would be otherwise missed.‚Å£  ‚Å£ This composite image contains X-ray data from our Chandra X-ray Observatory and the ROSAT telescope (purple), infrared data from our Spitzer Space Telescope (orange), and optical data from the SuperCosmos Sky Survey (blue) made by the United Kingdom Infrared Telescope.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Image description: This region looks like purple and blue drops of paint layered between streaks of orange and blue. There is color almost everywhere, though the blackness of space can be seen on the outer edges of the image. Stars are scattered all over; three shining stars nearly in a vertical line in the middle of the image stand out the most. There are bubbles, or cavities, that have been created by radiation and material blowing away from the surfaces of massive stars.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Credit: X-ray: NASA/CXC/PSU/L. Townsley et al; Optical: UKIRT; Infrared: NASA/JPL-Caltech‚Å£  ‚Å£ #NASA #Xray #Astronomy #Stars #Universe #Space #Abracadabra

Your screen isn't fuzzy‚Äîyou're looking at planets 130 light-years away.  Exoplanets, or planets beyond our solar system, are so small that we usually detect them by measuring the effect they have on their star: they may cause the star to wobble a bit, or make it a little less bright as they pass in front of it. But our @NASAWebb telescope is so powerful that it can spot, not just distant stars, but the much smaller worlds that orbit them.   The HR 8799 star system has long been of interest to astronomers for what it can tell us about how planets form, and Webb is giving us a better look at it than ever. Not only are we getting a direct look at these four gas giants, Webb's data tells us that these worlds are rich in carbon dioxide, suggesting that they formed similarly to Jupiter and Saturn in our home system. See some supersonic shockwaves üëÄ   You're looking at two T-38 jets, soaring faster than the speed of sound‚Äîflying in formation just 30 feet (9 meters) apart. This image was taken using a technique called schlieren photography, which measures the flow of air around objects. When an aircraft goes supersonic (about 760 miles an hour, or 1220 kph, at sea level), it sends shockwaves through the air, rapid pressure changes which are responsible for the sonic boom you may hear on the ground.   This photo was taken by a @NASA aircraft in 2019‚Äîthe first flight ever to capture interacting shockwaves from two supersonic aircraft. Images like these are helping us design our @NASAAero X-59 aircraft, which aims to fly at supersonic speeds without creating loud sonic booms. X-59 is currently gearing up for its first flight later this year.   Image description: Two jet planes, seen from below, fly through a bright blue background. Dark lines, indicating the path of their shockwaves, extend at trailing angles from the jets, with bright red trails visible very close to the jets. This image was originally monochromatic and is shown here as a colorized composite.   Credit: NASA   #NASA #Airplane #AircraftPhotography #T38 #Supersonic #Aeronautics #AvGeek #Aviation #Photography

A firestorm of stars üî•  This @NASAHubble image takes a close-up look at Centaurus A, one of the brightest galaxies in Earth's night sky. At some point in the past, Centaurus A collided with another galaxy; the resulting shockwaves caused clouds of hydrogen gas to compress, setting off a firestorm of newly-forming stars. These stellar hot spots can be seen in red here, peeking out through the galaxy's dust.  Hubble took this image in 2010 with its Wide Field Camera 3. Installed on the orbiting telescope in 2009, WFC3 can study the universe in wavelengths from the ultraviolet to the near-infrared‚Äîand all the visible light in between. Cosmic bubble gum‚Å£ ü´ß  ‚Å£ This candy-colored confection is a planetary nebula nicknamed the Little Gem Nebula. Located 6,000 light-years away from us in the constellation of Sagittarius, this Little Gem has a rather interesting shape ‚Äì and that‚Äôs thanks to the way it was made.‚Å£  ‚Å£ When stars like the Sun enter ‚Äúretirement,‚Äù they shed their outer layers into space to create glowing clouds of gas called planetary nebulae. This ejection of mass is uneven, and planetary nebulae can have very complex shapes. The Little Gem took on the shape of a bright, enclosed central bubble with filament-like structures surrounded by a more diffuse bubble.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Scientists believe that the stellar wind from the central star propels the outward-flowing material, sculpting the nebula‚Äôs elongated shape. As this fast wind smashes through the slower-moving cloud, it creates particularly bright blowouts at the bubble‚Äôs outer layers.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Image description: The Little Gem Nebula looks like two blue and purple cloudy bubbles, with bright streaks of red in the middle and on the outer edges. There is a bright dot near the center of the nebula. The rest of the image is black.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Credit: ESA/Hubble & NASA, Acknowledgment: Judy Schmidt‚Å£  ‚Å£ #NASA #Hubble #Nebula #Color #Astrophotography #Bubble

A cosmic cherry on top üçí‚Å£ ‚Å£ @NASAWebb treated us to a sweet perspective: Herbig-Haro 49/50‚Äîa towering swirl from a nearby protostar‚Äîis (coincidentally) topped with a multi-hued spiral galaxy.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Herbig-Haro objects are outflows produced by jets launched from a nearby, forming star. The outflows, which can extend for light-years, plow into a denser region of material. This creates shock waves, heating the material to higher temperatures. The material then cools by emitting light at visible and infrared wavelengths.‚Å£ ‚Å£ The galaxy that appears, by chance, at the tip of this cosmic soft-serve is a much more distant, face-on spiral galaxy. It has a prominent central bulge represented in blue, filled with older stars. The bulge also shows hints of ‚Äúside lobes,‚Äù suggesting that this could be a barred spiral galaxy. Reddish clumps within the spiral arms show the locations of warm dust and groups of forming stars.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Image description: This cosmic image is dominated with billowing clouds of orange-red gas, rich in detail. Status: It‚Äôs complicated.‚Å£  ‚Å£ @NASAWebb captures a rare cosmic phenomenon in this new image, called an Einstein ring. What may look like one strangely-shaped galaxy is actually two galaxies separated by a large distance. The closer galaxy sits at the center of the image, while the more distant background galaxy appears to be wrapped around the closer galaxy, forming a ring.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Now, stay with us here ‚Äî the light from the more distant galaxy is being bent (or lensed) by the closer, massive galaxy. This is possible because spacetime, the fabric of the universe itself, is bent by mass. Therefore, the light traveling through space and time is bent, as well. While too subtle to observe on smaller scales, the astronomical proportions allow us to observe the curvature of light.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Only at the perfect alignment ‚Äî between the lensed object and the lensing object ‚Äî can this distinctive Einstein ring shape be seen.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Image description: In the center is an elliptical galaxy, seen as an oval-shaped glow around a small bright core. Around this is wrapped a broad band of light, appearing like a spiral galaxy stretched and warped into a ring, with bright blue lines drawn through it where the spiral arms have been stretched into circles. A few distant objects are visible around the ring on a black background.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Credit: ESA/Webb, NASA & CSA, G. Mahler ‚Å£ Acknowledgement: M. A. McDonald‚Å£  ‚Å£ #NASA #Space #Webb #JWST #Telescope #Einstein #Stars #Phenomenon #Rare

Ravioli, ravioli, give me the formuoli‚Ä¶   The waters of the Patagonian Shelf have it all for the phytoplankton that bloom off Argentina, and we‚Äôll let you in on the secret formula: Airborne dust from the land, currents rich in iron, and upwelling from the ocean‚Äôs depths. This trio provides abundant nutrients for the tiny aquatic organisms that paint the ocean in shades of green and blue.   Phytoplankton bloom during the spring and summer in the South Atlantic Ocean, thriving on the long days of sunshine. The various colors represent a mix in communities as they change throughout the months-long bloom based on nutrient availability and environmental factors.   The exact types of phytoplankton present during a bloom can be a challenge to identify with remote sensing imagery. Birds of a feather, we should stick together A binary pair of actively forming stars is responsible for this shimmering hourglass of gas and dust. Here, @NASAWebb‚Äôs ability to see near-infrared light reveals incredible detail and structure in Lynds 483 (L483).The two protostars lie in the center of the hourglass shape, ejecting gas and dust. When more recent cosmic material clashes with old, the varying densities cause the shimmering twists and twirls you see in this image. There are black ‚Äúvoids‚Äù where stars don‚Äôt shine through (particularly to the left of the bottom part of the hourglass)‚Äîthis is where dust is so thick that little starlight penetrates. Even Webb, which is designed to see through dust and gas, only perceives the background stars as dim pinpoints of light. Above and below the flattened disk at the center, the dust is thinner and the bright light from the stars shines through, forming the large semi-transparent orange cones that glow around the outline of the hourglass.Millions of years from now, when the stars have finished forming, and have swept the area clean, they may each be about the mass of our Sun. All that may remain is a tiny disk of gas and dust where planets may eventually form.Read more at the link in @nasawebb‚Äôs bio. Image credit: NASA, ESA, CSA, STScI#Space #Stars #NASA #ESA #JWST #Astronomy #SXSW

What lies beneath‚Å£  ‚Å£ In this image, Venus may look like a serene planet, with white and tan clouds reminding us of a cozy cup of coffee. In reality, Venus is a world of intense heat, crushing atmospheric pressure, and clouds of corrosive acid.‚Å£  ‚Å£ The clouds seen here are comprised of sulfuric acid particles, as opposed to water droplets or ice crystals like on Earth. On top of being made of corrosive acid, these Venusian clouds whip around the planet at nearly over 200 mph (322 kph), circling the planet in about four and a half days.‚Å£  ‚Å£ So far, we‚Äôve got acidic clouds and hurricane-force winds. Underneath the clouds lies extreme heat and pressure: Venus is hotter even than the innermost planet, Mercury. Venus‚Äô thick atmosphere traps heat in a runaway greenhouse effect, giving it surface temperatures hot enough to melt lead! Finally, the surface pressure on Venus is 92 times that of Earth‚Äôs. To experience that pressure on our home planet, you‚Äôd have to dive more than 3,000 feet (915 m) into the ocean.‚Å£  ‚Å£ So why do we study this seeming hellscape of a planet? Although it‚Äôs not currently habitable, Venus lies within the Sun‚Äôs "Goldilocks zone," and may have been habitable before Earth. We want to understand how Venus became an inferno-like world when it has so many other characteristics similar to ours. Future missions like DAVINCI, VERITAS, and EnVision will seek to answer this question.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Image description: The clouds on Venus are mostly white, with patches of tan that bring to mind milk swirling through a cup of coffee. The rest of the image is black.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech‚Å£  ‚Å£ #NASA #Venus #Planet #Exploration #Astronomy

‚ÄúLook again at that dot. That‚Äôs here. That‚Äôs home. That‚Äôs us.‚Äù ‚Äî Carl Sagan, "Pale Blue Dot," 1994‚Å£‚Å£  ‚Å£‚Å£ Our Voyager 1 spacecraft took this iconic image of Earth 35 years ago. Voyager 1 was so far away ‚Äî 3.7 billion miles (6 billion km) ‚Äî from the Sun that, from its vantage point, Earth was just a point of light about a pixel in size. Truly a ‚ÄúPale Blue Dot.‚Äù‚Å£‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ Mission managers commanded the spacecraft to look back toward home for a final time. It snapped a series of 60 images that were used to create the first ‚Äúfamily portrait‚Äù of our solar system.‚Å£‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ Carl Sagan was a prominent planetary scientist who was a consultant and adviser to NASA beginning in the 1950s. He also was a member of the Voyager Imaging Team. He had the original idea in 1981 to use the cameras on one of the two Voyager spacecraft to image Earth. He realized that because the spacecraft were so far away the images might not show much. This was precisely why Sagan and other members of the Voyager team felt the images were needed ‚Äî they wanted humanity to see Earth‚Äôs vulnerability and that our home world is just a tiny, fragile speck in the cosmic ocean.‚Å£‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ After snapping the Pale Blue Dot and other ‚Äúfamily photos,‚Äù Voyager 1 powered off its cameras forever to save its energy for the long journey ahead. In August 2012, Voyager 1 entered interstellar space. It‚Äôs now the most distant human-made object ever.‚Å£‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ Image description: Earth is a single, bright blue pixel in the vastness of space. Rays of sunlight scattered within the camera optics stretch across the scene, one of which happens to have intersected dramatically with Earth. The original image was taken on Feb. 14, 1990. What you see here is an updated version from 2020 using modern image-processing software and techniques.‚Å£‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ Image credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech‚Å£‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ #NASA #Earth #PaleBlueDot #Astrophotography #Voyager #Space #Perspective

Look up, let your hair down ‚Äì howl if you like ‚Äì for it‚Äôll be a full moon!‚Å£  ‚Å£ After cozying up to Venus, Jupiter, and Mars earlier this month, the Moon reaches peak illumination on Feb. 12.‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ Looking at the Moon with only your eyes, you‚Äôll see mostly areas of white and gray. The gray patches are solidified volcanic lava flows. When the Moon was young, its interior was still molten, and magma would erupt onto its surface. The lighter-colored areas are called the highlands, and show the earliest crust on the Moon, dominated by a type of rock called anorthosite.‚Å£‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ What you see on the Moon with just your eyes will vary depending on your eyesight. Give yourself plenty of time for your eyes to adjust and look carefully. Looking with binoculars or a telescope will reveal more details, like mountain ridges and crater chains.‚Å£‚Å£  ‚Å£ For better viewing of craters and mountains, try phases other than the full moon. The shadows on the surface will be more pronounced, and help distinguish features you might otherwise miss.‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ Image description: In this picture from May 25, 2021, the nearly full moon rises over National Harbor in Fort Washington, Maryland. The Moon is just under the tip of the triangle shape formed by a structure. Some buildings and water can be seen in the background, while a few people are in the dimly lit foreground.‚Å£‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ Credit: NASA/Bill Ingalls‚Å£‚Å£ ‚Å£‚Å£ #NASA #Moon #FullMoon #Stargazing #Astronomy

Vintage with a twist ‚Äì er‚Ä¶ tilt.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Voyager 2 captured this image of Saturn and two of its moons, Rhea and Dione, on July 21, 1981. In this picture, Rhea is below and to the left of Saturn, while Dione is directly below the massive planet.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Rhea looks itty-bitty in this picture, yet it‚Äôs Saturn‚Äôs second-largest moon! Rhea is small, cold, and airless - very similar to sister moons Dione, pictured here, and Tethys. How cold is Rhea? It‚Äôs as ‚Äúwarm‚Äù as -281¬∫F (-174¬∫C) in sunlit areas, ranging down to -364¬∫F (-220¬∫C) in the shade.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Rhea appeared as a tiny dot to astronomers until the Voyager (1 and 2) encounters in 1980 and 1981. The Voyager images showed that Rhea‚Äôs features could be divided into two regions: heavily cratered terrain with craters larger than 25 miles (40 kilometers) across and a second type of area in parts of the polar and equatorial region with craters less than 25 miles (40 kilometers) across. This difference may indicate there was a major resurfacing event some time in Rhea‚Äôs history.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Dione is Saturn‚Äôs fourth-largest moon. It also has terrain with varying amounts of craters, along with fractured areas that often cut through its plains and craters. These fractures suggest Dione experienced tectonic activity in its past. The fractured areas are seen in Voyager images as bright and thin wispy lines. Later, flybys by our Cassini spacecraft showed these ‚Äúwisps‚Äù as bright canyon ice walls.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Rhea and Dione were both discovered by Giovanni Cassini, and both get their names from Greek mythology.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Image description: Saturn is tilted to the side in this image. It is yellowish, with a brighter, buttery yellow at its middle, where the planet‚Äôs rings surround it. Below Saturn are two small dots: These are two of its moons, Rhea and Dione. They all stand out against the darkness of space.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech‚Å£  ‚Å£ #NASA #Saturn #Rhea #Dione #Astronomy #Voyager #Cassini

Today, Jan. 23, is our annual NASA Day of Remembrance. On this day, we commemorate and honor all NASA employees, including the crews of Apollo 1, Challenger STS-51L, and Columbia STS-107, who lost their lives while furthering the cause of exploration and discovery for the benefit of all. Each year, we celebrate their bravery, their lives, and the advancements made in human spaceflight.   Safety is one of our core values: We‚Äôre committed to a strong, data-driven safety culture and climate. As we explore low Earth orbit and prepare for missions to the Moon and Mars, it is vital that we always remember and implement the lessons of our past in our preparations for the future.   Image description: The Space Shuttle Columbia Memorial is seen during NASA's Day of Remembrance, Thursday, Jan. 23, 2025, at Arlington National Cemetery. The memorial, a stone slab with a black-and-gold plaque, stands behind two wreaths, one with red flowers and one with white. The photograph focuses on the plaque, which lists the crew of Columbia within an outline of the shuttle.   Credit: NASA/Bill Ingalls   #NASA #NASARemembers #Apollo #Columbia #Challenger

Stars hatched by a swan üåü  Our WISE telescope captured this image, released in June 2011, of a huge complex of star-forming clouds and stellar clusters in the constellation Cygnus. Star clusters are groups of stars that share an origin, forming at roughly the same time and location, and are tied together by gravity for up to millions or even billions of years.  Different types of stars have different life spans, so clusters will change over time as stars evolve. Some clusters might contain big, hot, O-type stars. Others might hold smaller, cooler stars that age and change over billions of years. Star clusters can contain anywhere from as few as a dozen stars to upwards of millions, and those stars can be spread out over a few light-years to hundreds of light-years.  WISE (Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer) was an infrared-wavelength astronomical space telescope. It was placed into hibernation in February 2011, having completed its primary astrophysics mission. Then, in 2013, the spacecraft was assigned a new mission as NEOWISE (Near-Earth Object Wide-Field Infrared Survey Explorer), to help find near-Earth asteroids and comets. Its mission ended on July 31, 2024.  Image description: This image is dominated by curving green clouds, except at top left and middle, where there are also red clouds. A few bright yellow stars shine through the most defined clouds. There are also tiny multicolored ‚Äì though mostly blue ‚Äì dots of light throughout the whole area.  Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/UCLA  #NASA #Swan #Telescope #Constellation #Astrophotography

Jewels just beyond the spider‚Äôs realm üï∑   Dust gets a bad rap, doesn‚Äôt it? It‚Äôs a nuisance in houses, but out in the Large Magellanic Cloud (LMC), it adds to the beauty of the scene. @NASAHubble captured this image of part of the LMC ‚Äì the outskirts of the Tarantula Nebula ‚Äì marked by gas, patches of dust, and many-colored stars.   The stars here get their different colors thanks to that dust: Dust absorbs and scatters blue light more than red light, allowing more of the red light to reach our telescopes, which makes the stars appear redder than they are.   Using Hubble observations of dusty nebulae in the Large Magellanic Cloud and other galaxies, researchers can study these dust grains, helping them better understand the role that cosmic dust plays in the formation of new stars and planets.   Image description: Multicolored stars are sprinkled mostly on the left side of the image, shining through clouds of gas and dust. Gas appears blue here, laced with brownish-orange patches of dust.   Credit: ESA/Hubble & NASA, C. Murray   #NASA #Astronomy #Hubble #Telescope #Stars #Dust

Along with our Perseverance rover, which touched down in Jezero Crater in 2021, Curiosity is helping us understand the ancient past of Mars, when it could have been home to microbial life. Black Holes: Cooked. Ate. Left no crumbs.   Recent studies show that black holes in the universe can create their own meals. Data from our @nasachandraxray Observatory and the Very Large Telescope (VLT) provide new evidence that outbursts from black holes can help cool down gas to feed themselves.   The centers of galaxy clusters contain the universe‚Äôs most massive galaxies, which harbor huge black holes with masses ranging from millions to tens of billions of times that of the Sun. Jets from these black holes are driven by the black holes feasting on gas.   The latest research supports a model where outbursts from the black holes trigger hot gas to cool and form narrow filaments of warm gas. Some of the warm gas in these filaments should then flow into the centers of the galaxies to feed the black holes, causing an outburst. The outburst causes more gas to cool and feed the black holes, leading to further outbursts - a cosmic buffet!   Image descriptions: A swipe-through of different galaxy clusters, each with a central black hole surrounded by patches and filaments of gas. In each image, a patch of purple with neon pink veins floats in the blackness of space, surrounded by flecks of light. At the center of each patch is a glowing, bright white dot. The bright white dots represent black holes. The purple patches represent hot X-ray gas, and the neon pink veins represent filaments of warm gas.   In the image of the Perseus Cluster on the left, the surrounding flecks of light are larger and brighter, making the individual galaxies they represent easier to discern. The purple gas has a blue tint, and the hot pink filaments appear solid, as if rendered with quivering strokes of a paintbrush. The Centaurus Cluster is on the right; in this image, the purple gas appears softer, with a more diffuse quality. The filaments are rendered in more detail, with feathery edges, and range in color from pale pink to neon red.   Credit: (X-ray:) ASA/CXC/SAO/V. Olivares et al.; Optical/IR: DSS; H-alpha: CFHT/SITELLE; Centaurus Cluster: (X-ray:) ASA/CXC/SAO/V. Olivaresi et al.; (Optical/IR:) ASA/ESA/STScI; H-alpha: ESO/VLT/MUSE; Image Processing: NASA/CXC/SAO/N. Wolk  #NASA #Space

Keep your eye on the donut and not on the hole.  Released in 2019, this is the first image of a black hole and its shadow, which represents a historic feat by an international network of radio telescopes called the Event Horizon Telescope (EHT). A black hole is an extremely dense object from which no light can escape. Anything that comes within a black hole‚Äôs ‚Äúevent horizon,‚Äù its point of no return, will be consumed, never to re-emerge, because of the black hole‚Äôs unimaginably strong gravity. Not unlike the Black Lodge.  In this image, you can see the shadow of the supermassive black hole in the center of Messier 87 (M87), an elliptical galaxy some 55 million light-years from Earth. This black hole is 6.5 billion times the mass of the Sun. Catching its shadow involved eight ground-based radio telescopes around the globe, operating together as if they were one telescope the size of our entire planet.  In memory of David Lynch, we will continue to explore the otherworldly and the unknown. We will focus not on the loss, but on what we gained from the years we shared this planet with you. We will see you in our dreams.  Image description: Using the Event Horizon Telescope, scientists obtained this image of the black hole at the center of galaxy M87, outlined by emission from hot gas swirling around it under the influence of strong gravity near its event horizon. The hot gas is shaped like a doughnut and is glowing a warm yellow color with reddish tint at its edges. The darkness of space is black in the background.  Credit: Event Horizon Telescope collaboration et al.  #DavidLynch #TwinPeaks #Doughnut #BlackHole #Shadow #EventHorizon #SupermassiveBlackHole #NASA #Space #Donut

Nothing like a clear view‚Å£  ‚Å£ @NASAHubble captured an image of this previously unexplored globular cluster in the Milky Way, Palomar 8. A globular cluster is a collection of tens of thousands to millions of stars tightly bound together by gravity in a spherical shape ‚Äì like a globe. Globular clusters generally form early in the galaxies‚Äô histories in regions rich in gas and dust. Since the stars form from the same cloud of gas as it collapses, they typically hover around the same age.‚Å£  ‚Å£ The density of stars at the centers of these groupings is so high that individual stars are hard to discern, even with powerful telescopes on Earth. However, Hubble can! This image is part of a study that uses Hubble to distinguish individual stars of the entire globular cluster system of the Milky Way. These observations will give us key information on the early stages of our galaxy.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Image description: Bright stars cluster against a black background. The stars are more densely concentrated in the center of the image. The stars appear mostly white, but bright red and blue stars are also visible sprinkled throughout the image.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Credit: NASA, ESA, and D. Multiple fires have been burning in Los Angeles County since early January. Smoke plumes from the fires can be seen over the Pacific Ocean from space, visible in this @NOAA-20 satellite image from Jan. 9. Powerful Santa Ana winds and a lack of rain created ‚Äúcritical‚Äù fire weather conditions in Southern California, according to the @nws, contributing to the rapid spread of the fires.   As of Jan. 10, the Palisades Fire in California has burned nearly 20,000 acres. This fire, along with many others in the area, have forced evacuations in and around the Los Angeles area, including our @NASAJPL facility. Historically, California‚Äôs fire season runs from June or July through October or early November. The hot, dry conditions that drive fire season are now present longer into the winter, fueled by a warmer climate. NASA just confirmed 2024 was the hottest year on record.   We continue to think of all our colleagues, friends, and first responders affected by the fires during this time.   Credit: NOAA-20 Satellite   Image description: Satellite image of southern California on Jan. 9, 2025. The land is mostly shades of tan and brown, with small patches of dark green vegetation in the northern part of the image. The lower left third of the image is dark blue ocean water. Large plumes of whitish gray smoke are streaming out over the water from the Palisades and Eaton Fires in the region. The further south smoke plume is larger and reaches further over the water.   #NASA #Earth #Space #PalisadesFire #EatonFire #California

Even as a star dies, its light endures‚Äîechoing across the cosmos.‚Å£  ‚Å£ The James Webb Space Telescope is giving astronomers an unprecedented look at the fine details and 3D structure of the dust and gas between the stars.‚Å£  ‚Å£ The space between the stars is not empty, but rather filled with filaments of dust and gas (known as the interstellar medium), which is often invisible until something illuminates it.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Here, a long-ago supernova explosion, acting like a flashbulb, has heated some of this interstellar material, causing it to glow in the infrared, creating a thermal ‚Äúlight echo.‚Äù‚Å£  ‚Å£ As the supernova illumination travels through space at the speed of light, the echo appears to expand. Click the link in @NASAWebb‚Äôs bio to read more and to see more images and a video showing the change over time.‚Å£  ‚Å£ The structures in these filaments are on a remarkably small scale of about 400 astronomical units, or less than one-hundredth of a light-year. (An astronomical unit, or AU, is the average Earth-Sun distance and is equal to 93 million miles or 150 million kilometers.)‚Å£  ‚Å£ Credit: NASA, ESA, CSA, STScI, J. Jencson (Caltech/IPAC)‚Å£  ‚Å£ Image descriptions: Two frames show an infrared light echo traveling from the lower left of the first image through the upper right of the second image. They are not perfectly contiguous due to how the data were collected. Each image is speckled with dozens of white stars, some showing Webb‚Äôs signature 8-point diffraction spikes, against the black background of space. The images also show tightly packed, glowing red filaments that resemble muscle fibers or wood grain.‚Å£  ‚Å£ #NASA #Space #JWST #SpaceTelescope #Telescope #Astronomy #Supernova #Stars

That‚Äôs no Moon‚Ä¶‚Å£ ‚Å£ Because it‚Äôs Mercury! No one would blame you for mistaking one for the other, though. The two bodies do have some visual similarities: Mercury is only slightly larger than our Moon, and they‚Äôre both gray and cratered. NASA‚Äôs MESSENGER spacecraft captured this visible and infrared light view of the planet on Jan. 14, 2008, about 80 minutes before it made its closest pass at a distance of about 17,000 miles (27,000 kilometers). MESSENGER would go on to conduct two more flybys of Mercury on Oct. 6, 2008, and Sept. 29, 2009.‚Å£ ‚Å£ MESSENGER ‚Äì which stands for Mercury Surface, Space Environment, Geochemistry and Ranging ‚Äì was the first spacecraft to orbit Mercury. Its primary goal was to study the geology, magnetic field, and chemical composition of the planet. It was the first mission to Mercury after Mariner 10, more than 30 years before.‚Å£ ‚Å£ One of the first things MESSENGER discovered was high concentrations of magnesium and calcium on Mercury‚Äôs night side. It also found large amounts of water in the outermost layer of Mercury‚Äôs atmosphere and revealed evidence of past volcanic activity on the surface.‚Å£ ‚Å£ The spacecraft completed its primary mission on March 17, 2012, having taken nearly 100,000 images of the surface of Mercury.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Image description: Mercury looks almost like a waning crescent moon in this image. About three-quarters of the planet are in the frame, with only a thin slice of it lit. The bright part stands out starkly against the darkness of space.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Credit: NASA/Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory/Carnegie Institution of Washington‚Å£ ‚Å£ #NASA #Mercury #MESSENGER #Flyby #Planet #Science #Astrophotography

Cozy up for a planet parade!   All month in January, look up at the night sky to see Venus, Mars, Saturn, and Jupiter. Mid-month, Venus and Saturn will pass near each other, cozying up on Jan. 17 and 18 before parting ways.   Next door, our planetary neighbor, Mars, will reach opposition this month, which happens when the planet lies directly on the opposite side of Earth from the Sun, forming a straight line.   On Jan. 3, the Quadrantid meteor shower will peak and be visible through Jan. 12. For those in the Northern Hemisphere, your best viewing options will occur after midnight with clear, dark skies.   Happy skywatching!   Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech   #NASA #Space #WhatsUp #Sky #Skywatching #Planets #SolarSystem #Astronomy

Planets: Let them cook!‚Å£ ‚Å£ A @NASAHubble study from 2003 suggested that the gigantic disks that gave rise to planets in the early universe were longer-lived than they should be, given the conditions of their environment. Old stars don‚Äôt have enough of the heavier elements that are necessary ingredients to form the planets. But how are they still able to cook at the ripe old age of 20 to 30 million years?‚Å£ ‚Å£ To answer this question, researchers used @NASAWebb to study stars in a nearby galaxy that, much like the early universe, lacks large amounts of heavy elements. The circles in the second image show the positions of the 10 stars surveyed. The researchers found that not only do some stars there have planet-forming disks, but that those disks are longer-lived than those seen around young stars in our Milky Way galaxy‚Äîconfirming Hubble‚Äôs original findings.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Image descriptions: ‚Å£ 1. The center of the image contains arcs of orange and pink that form a boat-like shape. One end of these arcs points to the top right of the image, while the other end point toward the bottom left. Another plume of orange and pink expands from the center to the top left of the image. To the right of this plume is a large cluster of white stars. There are various other white stars and a few galaxies of different sizes spread throughout the image.‚Å£ ‚Å£ 2. The second image is the same as the first, but annotated with 10 small, yellow circles overlaid at various points to indicate the positions of the stars surveyed in this study.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Credit: NASA, ESA, CSA, STScI, Olivia C. Jones (UK ATC), ‚Å£ Guido De Marchi (ESTEC), Margaret Meixner (USRA)‚Å£ ‚Å£ #NASA #Space #Webb #SpaceTelescope #Telescope #Planets #Formation #Stars

Sometimes you‚Äôve got to bloom before you glow. üåü   ...just like this rare Wolf-Rayet star did before going supernova. 15,000 light years away from the constellation Sagittarius, WR 124 shed its outer layers, resulting in halos of gas and dust that appear like a blooming flower‚Äîa fleeting phase that happens to only some stars before they explode.   In this composite image from @NASAChandraXray, @NASAWebb and WISE, WR 124 gleams as dozens of other bright stars surround it. X-rays from Chandra are colorized purple, while infrared frequencies captured from WISE are blue. Observations from Webb‚Äôs Near-Infrared and Mid-Infrared instruments are red, green, and blue.   The star itself is 30 times the mass of our Sun and has shed 10 Suns‚Äô worth of material so far. As the gas moves away and cools, cosmic dust forms, showering astronomers with a deeper insight into a crucial period in the early history of our universe. Stars similar to WR 124 first seeded the young universe with heavy elements forged in their cores ‚Äì elements that are now common in the universe‚Äôs current season, including on Earth.   Image description: A large eight-pointed star shines at the center of the image in white and blue hues. Surrounding it near the center are yellow clouds of dust, with outer portions of purple clouds of dust. Together, the star and dust resemble a blooming flower. Around it are purple specks and other blue eight-pointed stars. The black background of space the star sits against is glittered with additional stars.   Credit: X-ray: NASA/CXC/SAO; Infrared: (Herschel) ESA/NASA/Caltech, (Spitzer) NASA/JPL/Caltech, (WISE) NASA/JPL/Caltech; Infrared: NASA/ESA/CSA/STScI/Webb ERO Production Team; Image processing: NASA/CXC/SAO/J. These stars are seen here as blue and white lights, representing the X-rays they give off that are detected by Chandra. They‚Äôre surrounded by swirls of gas‚Äîthe ‚Äúpine needles‚Äù of the tree‚Äîwith green representing light in the visible spectrum.In the first image, optical data (in green and violet) was captured by astrophotographer Michael Clow from his telescope in Arizona in November 2024. In the second image of the cluster, released in 2023, optical data (in green) was observed by the National Science Foundation‚Äôs WIYN 0.9-meter telescope on Kitt Peak in Arizona.The images have been rotated clockwise by about 160 degrees from the astronomer‚Äôs standard of North pointing upward, so that it appears like the top of the tree is toward the top of the image.Image descriptions:1. Mimas is about 115,000 miles (186,000 km) from Saturn‚Äîhalf the distance from the Earth to the Moon‚Äîand takes just 22.5 hours to make a lap around the giant planet.   Mimas can be seen at the very bottom of this image, which was taken by our Cassini spacecraft in 2005. Behind it, Saturn‚Äôs northern latitudes shine in a cool blue, with shadows from its rings forming long, dark lines on the atmosphere. Stars sparkle into life ‚ú®  This glittering cluster of 3,000 stars is known as Westerlund 2, named for the Swedish astronomer, Bengt Westerlund, who discovered it. This star cluster is between 6 to 13 light-years across, and is "only" about 2 million years old‚Äîa very long time for us, but a blink of an eye for a star.   Because this star cluster is so young, many of its stars have not yet ignited the hydrogen in their cores; the red dots scattered throughout this image are newly-forming stars, still wrapped in their gas-and-dust cocoons. Westerlund 2 is about 20,000 light-years from Earth, visible in the constellation Carina.  Image description: A bright arc of multicolored gas, in shades ranging from orange and red to blue and purple, sweeps across the left and bottom of this cosmic image. Within the arc, countless bright red stars are clumped closely together, with other blue and red stars scattered throughout the image.  Credit: NASA, ESA, the Hubble Heritage Team (STScI/AURA), A. Nota (ESA/STScI), and the Westerlund 2 Science Team  #NASA #Universe #Space #Galaxy #Astrophotography #Stars

Stars / In your multitudes / Scarce to be counted‚ú®‚Å£  ‚Å£ NASA astronaut @astro_pettit used a homemade tracking device to capture this starfield from a window on the SpaceX Dragon crew spacecraft docked to the International Space Station.‚Å£  ‚Å£ To get a stellar view like this, Pettit took a 25-second-long exposure with an ISO (camera light sensitivity) of 3200. With a longer exposure ‚Äì that is, leaving the camera‚Äôs shutter open for a longer period of time ‚Äì more light falls on the camera‚Äôs sensor. On top of that, the cameras the astronauts often use are designed to be more sensitive in low-light situations. All this means they‚Äôre more likely to capture bright stars in their images.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Images of the Earth from orbit are typically taken with exposures just right to image the bright planet, but too short to record many stars, which are far dimmer in comparison.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Image description: Looking through an oval, we can see space blanketed by white stars. There are two blue smudges: these are the Large and Small Magellanic Clouds, two irregular dwarf galaxies. Moving down, Earth‚Äôs atmosphere glows red and green.‚Å£  ‚Å£ Credit: NASA/Don Pettit‚Å£  ‚Å£ #NASA #Astrophotography #Stars #SpaceStation #Astronaut #ISS #Photography #Earth #Space

It‚Äôs MY turn to shine.   Several million young stars are vying for attention in this @NASAHubble image of a star-forming nebula called 30 Doradus, or the Tarantula Nebula. At the time of release (April 16, 2012), this was one of the largest mosaic images ever assembled from Hubble photos; this image is roughly 650 light-years across!   Located 170,000 light-years away in the Large Magellanic Cloud, 30 Doradus is pretty stellar ‚Äì pun fully intended. It‚Äôs the brightest star-forming region in our galactic neighborhood, it‚Äôs home to the most massive stars ever seen, and no known star-forming region in our galaxy is as large or as prolific.   See the clouds of gas and dust at bottom left that almost look like waves you‚Äôd see at the beach? They were carved into that shape because of the ultraviolet light released by massive stars. In addition to sculpting the material around them, these brilliant stars may also be triggering new waves of star birth: when the ultraviolet radiation hits dense walls of gas, it creates shocks, which may create a new generation of offspring.   Image description: This turbulent scene of star birth takes shape in shades of deep blue, brownish red, and white. Millions of stars, some bigger and brighter than others, dot the landscape. At middle left, a bright area looks like white tendrils stretching outward. Directly below that are clouds carved into wave-like shapes.   Credit: NASA, ESA, D. Lennon and E. Sabbi (ESA/STScI), J. Anderson, S. E. de Mink, R. van der Marel, T. Sohn, and N. Walborn (STScI), N. Bastian (Excellence Cluster, Munich), L. Bedin (INAF, Padua), E. Bressert (ESO), P. All that is glitters is not gold‚Ä¶   But it may still be a galaxy. This sparkling field is Abell 2125, a galaxy cluster located 3 billion light-years away from us in the Ursa Minor constellation. Each golden yellow dot you see is an individual galaxy, captured in visible light by the Kitt Peak National Observatory. The purple dots and haze are gas clouds seen in X-ray light by @NASAChandraXray. X-rays are not part of the visible light spectrum, so they've been translated into color we can see in this image.   It takes billions of years to build a massive galaxy cluster like Abell 2125, which may contain thousands of galaxies. Since it‚Äôs so far away, this cluster also gives us insight into the early stages of galaxy cluster development, as well as the effects on galaxies within it. For example, data from Chandra, @NASAHubble, and the Very Large Array show that several galaxies in Abell 2125 are being stripped of their gas as they fall through hot, high-pressure clouds.   Image description: This entire image is covered with purple and gold dots. Slightly above center is the largest and brightest dot, a galaxy with four diffraction spikes. Throughout the image, but especially at upper left and bottom right, are purple clouds of gas that you can see through.   Credit: X-ray: NASA/CXC/SAO; Optical: NSF/NOIRLab/KPNO/F. Owen; Image Processing: NASA/CXC/SAO/J. Major, K. Arcand   #NASA #Chandra #Xray #Astronomy #Astrophotography #Galaxy #Gold #Telescope #Space

Rings and moons ü™ê  Saturn's moon Mimas stands alone in this ethereal image captured by our Cassini spacecraft in 2004. Mimas is the smallest of Saturn's major moons, checking in at less than 123 miles (198 km) wide. Its most prominent feature is a massive impact crater, with a small bump in the middle that draws comparisons to the Death Star from Star Wars.  Saturn's rings stretch across the bottom of this image, with a small gap near the top known as the Cassini division. These rings cast shadows on the cool, blue-streaked backdrop of Saturn's northern hemisphere, fading into darkness on Saturn's night side.  Image description: Two bands of color arc across this photo of space: a brownish-tan streak across the bottom of the image, and blue-white streaks arcing downward from left to right. Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/Space Science Institute  #NASA #Space #Universe #Saturn #SolarSystem #Cassini #RingOfTheDay

Our Sun, and solar system, are about halfway from the Milky Way's center‚Äîwhich is why you can see the galaxy shining in the night sky if you're far from cities and bright lights. Full moon tonight!  Friday, Nov. 15, is a great opportunity to see our fourth supermoon in a row‚Äîand the last one of 2024. November's full moon is sometimes called the Beaver Moon: November is when beavers prepare for the winter by fortifying dams and stocking their food supply.  A supermoon takes place when the full moon is near perigee, its closest point to Earth: a distance of about 226,000 miles, or 364,000 kilometers. When the full moon is at its furthest distance from Earth‚Äîabout 253,000 miles (407,000 km), its apogee‚Äîit's sometimes known as a micromoon.  Visit moon.nasa.gov to learn more about our orbiting neighbor!  Image description: A hazy, orange-red moon rises over a subway car, which is moving so quickly that it is slightly blurred in the image. The night sky is a uniform shade of very dark blue, but a few clouds can be seen passing in front of the bright moon.  Credit: NASA/Bill Ingalls  #NASA #Space #Moon #Supermoon #FullMoon #BeaverMoon #Skywatcher

Tiny but mighty üí™  Saturn ice moon Mimas wears its history on its surface. The tiny moon ‚Äì only 247 miles (397 km) across ‚Äì is covered in impact craters dating from the turbulent beginnings of our solar system.   Its most distinguishing feature is a giant impact crater named Herschel (not shown here), after the English astronomer who discovered Mimas in 1789. Shock waves from the Herschel impact may have caused the fractures, also called chasmata, on the opposite side of Mimas.   Puzzlingly, Mimas appears to be frozen solid. Mimas is closer to Saturn and has a much more elongated orbit than Enceladus, another of Saturn‚Äôs icy moons, so it should have more tidal heating than Enceladus. Yet Enceladus has geysers of water, which implies internal heat, while Mimas has one of the most heavily cratered surfaces in the solar system, which suggests a frozen surface that has lasted long enough to preserve all those craters.   This paradox has prompted the "Mimas Test" ‚Äì any theory that claims to explain Enceladus‚Äô partially thawed water must also explain Mimas‚Äô entirely frozen water.   Image description: Mimas, a small moon with a heavily cratered surface, is in sharp focus against the hazy edge of Saturn‚Äôs atmosphere. Half of Mimas is visible, while the right side is in shadow. The image is in black and white.   Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/Space Science Institute   #NASA #Saturn #Astronomy #Moon #Crater #SolarSystem #Space #BlackAndWhite
